21. ao deus aliquis, &c. Baehrens and, on different grounds, John prefer to read ‘aut deus aliquis,' δια, and there is perhaps a certain want of logical pre- cision in the way in which the writer presents what is really intended as a dual alternative. The first hypothesis is,-ac· cording to John, the transportation of one of the two parties (aut vos . . . aut illi) into the age of the other: the second the simultaneous reciproca] exchange of epochs (deus . . . repente mutasset). But it is possible to be too exacting in the way of precision of statement: the ac deus . . . mutasset clause seems rather to have been added in the way of an after- thought: Novak indeed, following Mul- ler's suggestion, rejects it altogether, as having been added by some one who remembered the well-known passage in Horace (Sat. i. 1, 15).
